// emoji-data.ts — vendored emoji dataset (scher emoji picker, 2026-07-14 wave).
//
// PROVENANCE: rows below are compacted from unicode-emoji-json v0.7.0
// (https://github.com/muan/unicode-emoji-json), data-by-emoji.json, itself
// built from unicode.org's emoji data files (CLDR / Unicode emoji-test.txt).
// Fetched 2026-07-14. Upstream LICENSE: MIT, Copyright (c) 2019 Mu-An Chiou.
// This file: same MIT terms carry forward with the data.
//
// COMPACTION: each upstream entry has {name, slug, group, emoji_version,
// unicode_version, skin_tone_support}. The picker only needs the emoji glyph,
// a human name (search target), and a coarse group (category tabs) — slug,
// version fields, and skin_tone_support are dropped (slug is name.replace(/
// /g,'_'), recoverable if ever needed; versions and the tone flag are unused
// by this picker, which defers skin-tone selection entirely, honestly — see
// emoji-picker.ts's file header). That drop takes the source JSON from
// ~387KB to ~70KB here.
//
// GROUP CODES map to the 9 canonical Unicode emoji groups, short for size:
//   smileys    → Smileys & Emotion
//   people     → People & Body
//   nature     → Animals & Nature
//   food       → Food & Drink
//   travel     → Travel & Places
//   activities → Activities
//   objects    → Objects
//   symbols    → Symbols
//   flags      → Flags
//
// SEARCH: emoji-picker.ts tokenizes `name` at query time — no separate
// keywords field. unicode-emoji-json's names are full CLDR annotations
// ('grinning face with smiling eyes'), which already carry the words a
// search would use; a richer keyword thesaurus (emojilib) was surveyed but
// not vendored — YAGNI unless search misses prove it's needed (QUERIES.md).
//
// Row shape: [emoji, name, group]. Order preserved from upstream (Unicode's
// canonical display order — category tabs render in this order too).
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

